<quantity box="[163,240,1727,1748]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="704" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
width (
<tableCitation box="[325,407,1726,1748]" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="7.[163,227,1622,1643]" captionText="Table 2. Morphometric measures of each species collected. Range (min–max) in parenthesis" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Table 2</tableCitation>
). Colour: usually pink with black concentric lines compact (
<figureCitation box="[470,554,1757,1779]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="8.[145,225,1538,1560]" captionTargetBox="[147,1426,197,1497]" captionTargetId="figure-140@8.[145,1428,195,1498]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 4. Pictures of Chiton species from the south-eastern Pacific. A, Chiton barnesii live specimen from La Pampilla, Coquimbo, Chile (29°26’11’’S, 71°18’20’’W). B, Chiton stokesii live specimen from Santa Rosa, Ecuador (2°12’39’’S, 80°56’45’’W). C, Chiton cumingsii live specimen from Lagunillas, Coquimbo, Chile (30°06’13’’S, 71°22’59’’W). D, Chiton granosus live specimen from Antofagasta, Chile (23°40’10’’S, 70°24’29’’W). E, Chiton magnificus live specimen from Lagunillas, Coquimbo, Chile (30°06’13’’S, 71°22’59’’W). F, Chiton magnificus live specimen from Puerto del Hambre, Punta Arenas, Chile (53°36’44’’S, 70°55’43’’W)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300361" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300361/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
), some individuals can be almost black; jugal area usually more vivid colour. Body shape: oval to elongated-oval, middle dorsal elevation. Slit formula: 12–15/1/10–16. Plates: intermediate plates separated by space not exposed mantle, slightly overlapping one over the other, lines of growth in intermediate plates apparent to the naked eye (
<figureCitation box="[955,1031,1509,1531]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="14.[145,224,1332,1354]" captionTargetBox="[147,1426,197,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-278@14.[145,1428,195,1292]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 10. Chiton cumingsi, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, valve I, dorsal view; B, valve V, dorsal view; C, valve VIII, dorsal view; D, valve VIII, lateral view; E, valve VI, detail of tegmentum in central area; F, valve VI, central and lateral areas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496115" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496115/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). Intermediate plate with numerous aesthetes (
<figureCitation box="[966,1108,1540,1562]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="15.[164,244,1330,1352]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-260@15.[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 11. Chiton cumingsii, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, C, dorsal and ventral scales and marginal spicules; B, D, radula." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496117" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496117/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 11E, F</figureCitation>
). Tail valve back straight (
<figureCitation box="[836,937,1570,1592]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="14.[145,224,1332,1354]" captionTargetBox="[147,1426,197,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-278@14.[145,1428,195,1292]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 10. Chiton cumingsi, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, valve I, dorsal view; B, valve V, dorsal view; C, valve VIII, dorsal view; D, valve VIII, lateral view; E, valve VI, detail of tegmentum in central area; F, valve VI, central and lateral areas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496115" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496115/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
). Apophyses: moderately short, connected by short jugal lamina, delicately denticulate, clearly triangular and trapezoidal intermediate valves in valve series (
<figureCitation box="[984,1145,1662,1684]" captionStart="Figure 10" captionStartId="14.[145,224,1332,1354]" captionTargetBox="[147,1426,197,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-278@14.[145,1428,195,1292]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figure 10. Chiton cumingsi, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, valve I, dorsal view; B, valve V, dorsal view; C, valve VIII, dorsal view; D, valve VIII, lateral view; E, valve VI, detail of tegmentum in central area; F, valve VI, central and lateral areas." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496115" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496115/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 10B, C, F</figureCitation>
). Perinotum: moderately broad, dorsally with imbricated, flat and triangular scales (
<figureCitation box="[910,1036,1724,1746]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="15.[164,244,1330,1352]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-260@15.[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 11. Chiton cumingsii, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, C, dorsal and ventral scales and marginal spicules; B, D, radula." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496117" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496117/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 11A, C</figureCitation>
). Spicules at the ventral side of the perinotum (
<figureCitation box="[966,1064,1754,1776]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="15.[164,244,1330,1352]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-260@15.[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 11. Chiton cumingsii, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, C, dorsal and ventral scales and marginal spicules; B, D, radula." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496117" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496117/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 11C</figureCitation>
). Radula: central tooth rounded and hooked. The major lateral rounded (
<figureCitation box="[1285,1410,1785,1807]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="15.[164,244,1330,1352]" captionTargetBox="[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetId="figure-260@15.[163,1443,195,1290]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 11. Chiton cumingsii, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 19.5 mm, 05.01.2015: A, C, dorsal and ventral scales and marginal spicules; B, D, radula." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5496117" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5496117/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 11B, D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[827,1442,1848,1901]" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">
<emphasis box="[827,987,1848,1869]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Distribution:</emphasis>
We found this species from Lobitos (~ 
<geoCoordinate box="[851,891,1879,1901]" degrees="4" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="704" precision="55555" value="-4.0">4°S</geoCoordinate>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[913,968,1879,1900]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Peru</collectingCountry>
to Quellón (~ 
<geoCoordinate box="[1128,1183,1879,1901]" degrees="43" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="9" pageNumber="704" precision="55555" value="-43.0">43°S</geoCoordinate>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[1204,1266,1878,1900]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Chile</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[1282,1348,1878,1900]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="1.[827,914,1448,1470]" captionTargetBox="[834,1445,201,1399]" captionTargetId="figure-556@1.[827,1448,195,1408]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figure 1. Map showing sampling localities. Lines represent the geographical distribution of each Chiton species: 1, Chiton stokesii; 2, Chiton granosus; 3, Chiton cumingsii; 4, Chiton magnificus; 5, Chiton barnesii." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300355" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300355/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="704">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). It was
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300365" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5300365" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300365/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" startId="10.[145,223,1341,1363]" targetBox="[148,1426,199,1298]" targetPageId="10">
<paragraph blockId="10.[145,1425,1341,1393]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[145,248,1341,1363]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Figure 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1828" box="[259,420,1341,1363]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="barnesii">
<emphasis box="[259,420,1341,1363]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Chiton barnesii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 20.0 mm, 05.01.2015: A, C, dorsal and ventral scales and marginal spicules; B, D, radula, head of major lateral tooth has one denticle.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="10.[145,760,1431,1484]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">
<materialsCitation country="Peru" latitude="-41.0" location="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" specimenCount="1">
previously reported from Paita (~ 
<geoCoordinate box="[532,570,1431,1453]" degrees="5" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" precision="55555" value="-5.0">5°S</geoCoordinate>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[592,646,1431,1452]" name="Peru" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Peru</collectingCountry>
to Puerto Montt (~ 
<geoCoordinate box="[245,299,1462,1484]" degrees="41" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" precision="55555" value="-41.0">41°S</geoCoordinate>
), 
<collectingCountry box="[318,379,1461,1483]" name="Chile" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Chile</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Marincovich L" box="[394,603,1461,1483]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" pagination="42 - 49" refId="ref11377" refString="Marincovich L. 1973. Intertidal mollusks of Iquique, Chile. Natural History Museum. Los Angeles County Science Bulletin 16: 42 - 49." type="journal article" year="1973">Marincovich, 1973</bibRefCitation>
