</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[145,761,1524,1699]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">
<emphasis box="[145,252,1524,1545]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species is easy to differentiate from all other 
<taxonomicName box="[212,377,1555,1577]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[212,289,1555,1576]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Chiton</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in the area by their high number of ribs in all plates with small grains. In the head valve, they have more than 40 ribs of grains. This species has been introduced in the Canary Islands (
<geoCoordinate box="[663,756,1647,1669]" degrees="28" direction="north" minutes="06" orientation="latitude" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" precision="925" value="28.1">28°06’N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate box="[145,239,1677,1699]" degrees="15" direction="west" minutes="25" orientation="longitude" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" precision="925" value="-15.416667">15°25’W</geoCoordinate>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Arias A &amp; Anadon N" box="[262,507,1677,1699]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" pagination="593 - 596" refId="ref10776" refString="Arias A, Anadon N. 2013. Tonicia atrata and Chiton cumingsii (Polyplacophora: Chitonidae): First records in European waters. Zootaxa 3626: 593 - 596." type="journal article" year="2013">Arias &amp; Anadón 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[145,761,1740,1885]" lastBlockId="11.[827,1443,197,372]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="706" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">
<emphasis box="[145,590,1740,1762]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Notes on designation of type material:</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus box="[655,760,1740,1762]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">lectotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[194,349,1771,1793]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">paralectotype</typeStatus>
material comprise a single lot in the collections of the Natural History Museum, London (
<collectionCode box="[152,257,1832,1854]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
) (
<figureCitation box="[277,338,1832,1854]" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="10.[145,223,1341,1363]" captionTargetBox="[148,1426,199,1298]" captionTargetId="figure-277@10.[145,1428,195,1301]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="Figure 6. Chiton barnesii, Chile, Coquimbo, BL 20.0 mm, 05.01.2015:A, C, dorsal and ventral scales and marginal spicules; B, D, radula, head of major lateral tooth has one denticle." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300365" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300365/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). It is probable that some of Frembly’s specimens were deposited in the 
<collectionCode box="[557,664,1863,1884]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
via the collections of contemporaries, such as Hugh Cuming and J. E. Gray, although there is nothing to link any of this early material to Frembly directly (
<collectionCode box="[1295,1312,1492,1513]" name="Tavera, Department of Geology and Geophysics" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">T</collectionCode>
. S. White, pers. comm). Type material for other species described by Frembly has also been attributed to the 
<collectionCode box="[1320,1424,1554,1575]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
collection (
<bibRefCitation author="Kaas P &amp; Van Belle RA &amp; Strack HL" box="[931,1121,1584,1606]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" refId="ref11224" refString="Kaas P, Van Belle RA, Strack HL. 2006. Monograph of living chitons (Mollusca: Polyplacophora) 6, Suborder Ischnochitonina (concluded): Schizochitonidae; Chitonidae, additions to Vols 1 - 5. Leiden: Brill / Backhuys." type="book" year="2006">
Kaas 
<emphasis box="[996,1053,1584,1606]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">et al.</emphasis>
, 2006
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bullock RC" box="[1134,1302,1584,1606]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" pagination="280 - 299" refId="ref10906" refString="Bullock RC. 1988 b. The systematics of the southern hemisphere chiton genera Radsia Gray, 1847, and Sypharochiton Thiele, 1893 (Mollusca: Polyplacophora: Chitonidae). Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 101: 280 - 299." type="journal article" year="1988">Bullock, 1988b</bibRefCitation>
), although the status of these specimens requires further careful investigation. In the original description of 
<taxonomicName authority=", Frembly (1827: 199)" authorityName=", Frembly" authorityPageNumber="199" authorityYear="1827" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="cumingsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">Chiton cumingsii</emphasis>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Frembly, JRN" box="[934,1162,1676,1698]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" pagination="193 - 205" refId="ref11064" refString="Frembly, JRN. 1827. A description of several new species of Chitones, found on the coast of Chili, in 1825, with a few remarks on the method of taking and preserving them. The Zoological Journal 3: 193 - 205." type="journal article" year="1827">Frembly (1827: 199)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
noted ‘A specimen also was found [showing] ... only seven valves, but inside the articulation of the other valve was plainly seen’. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[809,887,1768,1790]" class="Polyplacophora" family="Chitonidae" genus="Chiton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chitonida" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">Chiton</taxonomicName>
teratologies are rare (
<bibRefCitation author="Torres FI &amp; Ibanez CM &amp; Sanhueza VE &amp; Pardo-Gandarillas MC" box="[1137,1338,1768,1790]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" pagination="683 - 689" refId="ref12217" refString="Torres FI, Ibanez CM, Sanhueza VE, Pardo-Gandarillas MC. 2018. Mollusk freaks: new teratological cases on marine mollusks from the South Pacific Ocean. Latin American Journal of Aquatic Research 46: 683 - 689." type="journal article" year="2018">
Torres 
<emphasis box="[1216,1264,1768,1790]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="705">et al</emphasis>
., 2018
</bibRefCitation>
). There was only one teratological specimen of this species in the 
<collectionCode box="[850,953,1830,1851]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
collection, amongst a lot of 
<specimenCount box="[1256,1424,1829,1851]" pageId="10" pageNumber="705" type="generic">four specimens</specimenCount>
(NHMUKMUK 20190538/1–4) from the J. E. Gray Frembly (1927) (
<figureCitation box="[1020,1102,197,219]" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="11.[163,241,1548,1570]" captionTargetBox="[163,784,195,1509]" captionTargetId="figure-496@11.[163,784,195,1509]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 7. Type specimens of chitons: A, lectotype of Chiton cumingsii NHMUK 20190538/1; B, paralectotype of Chiton cumingsii NHMUK 20190538/2; C, neotype of Chiton granosus NHMUK 20190537/1. Scale bar 10 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5300367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5300367/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="706">Fig. 7B</figureCitation>
). The specimen closest to the potentially generalized dimensions given in Frembly’s original description (‘length two inches, breadth 1 3/10’; 5.0 × 
<quantity box="[962,1039,289,311]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="11" pageNumber="706" unit="cm" value="3.3">3.3 cm</quantity>
) has been designated the primary 
<typeStatus box="[827,936,320,342]" pageId="11" pageNumber="706">lectotype</typeStatus>
(
<collectionCode box="[954,1062,320,341]" country="United Kingdom" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34665" name="Natural History Museum, London" pageId="11" pageNumber="706" type="Museum">NHMUK</collectionCode>
20190538/1, dimensions, 4.2 × 
<quantity box="[827,905,351,372]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="11" pageNumber="706" unit="cm" value="2.3">2.3 cm</quantity>
).
</paragraph>
